1. cs.GT (Game Theory): The paper deals with the existence of approximate Nash equilibria in games, which is a central topic in game theory. 
2. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms): The paper presents a new proof for the results of Lipton et al., which involves algorithmic techniques and complexity analysis. 
3. cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence): The paper discusses the concept of Nash equilibrium, which is a key concept in AI and multi-agent systems. 
4. cs.CC (Computational Complexity): The paper deals with the complexity of finding approximate Nash equilibria, which is a computational problem. 
5. cs.IT (Information Theory): The paper provides bounds on the size of the support of approximate Nash equilibria, which can be seen as an information-theoretic problem.
